feat(map): persist and restore selected map type

This commit introduces functionality to save and automatically restore the user's selected map type (both standard Google Maps types and custom tile provider URLs) across app sessions.

The selected map type is now stored in SharedPreferences. When the MapViewModel is initialized, it attempts to load the previously selected map type.

Specific changes include:
- Added new preference keys `PREF_SELECTED_GOOGLE_MAP_TYPE` and `PREF_SELECTED_CUSTOM_TILE_URL`.
- Implemented `loadPersistedMapType()` to retrieve and apply the saved map type on startup. This function includes logic to validate saved custom URLs and fallback to defaults if a saved type is no longer valid.
- Modified `removeCustomTileProviderConfig` to also clear the custom URL from preferences if it was the selected one.
- Updated `selectCustomTileProvider` to save the selected custom URL to preferences and clear any selected Google Map type.
- Updated `setSelectedGoogleMapType` to save the selected Google Map type to preferences and clear any selected custom URL.
- Ensured that when a custom tile provider is selected, or an invalid one is attempted, the corresponding preference is updated or cleared.
- When loading, if a saved custom URL is no longer in the list of available custom tile providers or is invalid, it is cleared from preferences, and the map defaults to the standard Google Map type.
- Added error handling for loading persisted Google Map types in case the stored name is invalid.

- Enhanced build summaries and GitHub Actions integration
- Support for both scheduled builds and manual triggers

Deprecation:
- Mark runner-builld.yaml as deprecated with clear migration path
- Direct users to new infrastructure workflow for rust-builder builds
- Maintain backward compatibility with deprecation notices

Benefits:
- Better workflow organization and separation of concerns
- Centralized infrastructure management in single repository
- Cleaner build triggers and dependency management
- Production-ready images with proper versioning and caching

feat(ui): Add multi-state Quick Action button for menu bar display style

- Implements a fourth Quick Action button to cycle through menu bar display styles (Icon & Text, Icon Only, Text Only).
- Introduces a `MenuBarDisplayStyle` enum to manage the different states.
- The user's preference is saved to and loaded from UserDefaults, persisting across app launches.
- The button provides visual feedback by changing its icon and accent color for each state.
- `MenuBarLabelView` is now driven by this setting, dynamically updating the menu bar item's appearance.
- Uses the .id() modifier to ensure SwiftUI correctly re-renders the button's color when its state changes.

fix(ui): Correctly apply custom tint color to Quick Action symbols

The SF Symbol inside the QuickActionButton was not respecting the custom active tint color (e.g., green, orange) and was instead using the default system accent color.

This commit fixes the issue by explicitly applying the `tintColor` from the style to the symbol's `.foregroundStyle` modifier when the button is in its active state.

This ensures the icon's color perfectly matches the button's background and stroke tint, providing correct visual feedback.
